SIMPLE: plank
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Plank
<hw>Plank</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>planke</ets>,
OF. <ets>planque</ets>, <ets>planche</ets>, F. <ets>planche</ets>, fr.
L. <ets>planca</ets>; cf. Gr. <?/, <?/, anything flat and broad. Cf.
<er>Planch</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A broad piece of sawed timber,
differing from a board only in being thicker. See
<er>Board</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fig.: That which supports or upholds, as a board
does a swimmer.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His charity is a better <qex>plank</qex> than the faith of an
intolerant and bitter-minded bigot.</q> <rj><qau>Southey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>One of the separate articles in a declaration of the
principles of a party or cause; <as>as, a <ex>plank</ex> in the national
platform</as>.</def> <mark>[Cant]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Plank road</b></col>, <it>or</it> <col><b>Plank
way</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a road surface formed of planks.</cd>
<mark>[U.S.]</mark> -- <col><b>To walk the plank</b></col>, <cd>to walk
along a plank laid across the bulwark of a ship, until one overbalances
it and falls into the sea; -- a method of disposing of captives
practiced by pirates.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1095 --></p>

<p><ent>Plank</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Plank
<hw>Plank</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Planked</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Planking</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cover or lay with
planks; <as>as, to <ex>plank</ex> a floor or a ship</as>.</def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Planked</xex> with pine.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To lay down, as on a plank or table; to stake or pay
cash; <as>as, to <ex>plank</ex> money in a wager</as>.</def>
<mark>[Colloq. U.S.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To harden, as hat bodies, by felting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Wooden Manuf.)</fld> <def>To splice together the
ends of slivers of wool, for subsequent drawing.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Planked shad</b></col>, <cd>shad split open, fastened to
a plank, and roasted before a wood fire.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Planking</ent>⟦br⟧
